## Mandatory verification sequence (before any commit)

```bash
npx tsc --noEmit
npm run build
npm run lint
npx vitest run
```

All four must be green. `tsc --noEmit` is non-negotiable: vitest transpiles via esbuild without type-checking, and `next build` doesn’t type-check files outside the app’s import graph. Test files routinely escape both — only `tsc` catches type drift in tests.

## Architecture patterns

Hard rules — not suggestions. See linked handbook entries for rationale.

- **Mock/real parity.** Every data-layer function in `src/lib/data/` (and module data layers) branches on `isSupabaseConfigured()`. Both branches must be implemented and kept in sync. New features ship working in both modes. See [`principles/mock-real-parity.md`](https://github.com/rajivjc/engineering-handbook/blob/main/principles/mock-real-parity.md).
- **Server actions formula.** Every server action follows the same shape, in this order: `authn` (resolve user) → `authz` (role check) → `validate` (zod or equivalent) → `call` (data layer or RPC) → `revalidate` (path/tag) → `return` (typed result). No exceptions; if a step doesn’t apply, the missing step is a deliberate decision worth a comment.
- **Defense-in-depth authorization.** Three layers: route-level (layout guards), server-side (action role checks), and database-level (RLS policies). All three apply to every state-changing endpoint. See [`principles/defense-in-depth-authorization.md`](https://github.com/rajivjc/engineering-handbook/blob/main/principles/defense-in-depth-authorization.md).
- **Atomic state via RPC.** Multi-row mutations live inside a Postgres function called from a server action. No application-level multi-step mutations. See [`principles/atomic-state.md`](https://github.com/rajivjc/engineering-handbook/blob/main/principles/atomic-state.md).
- **Role hierarchy.** {{TODO: list roles in this project, highest privilege first. Example: `owner` > `manager` > `staff` > `member`. Document inheritance rules: does `owner` automatically grant all lower roles' permissions, or are roles disjoint?}}
- **Timezone.** {{TODO: project timezone (e.g., `Asia/Singapore`). All date/time math in the data layer must use this zone explicitly. No `new Date()` without timezone handling. A convention guard test fails CI if a bare `new Date()` appears in `src/lib/data/`.}}
- **`server-only` import rule.** Every file in `src/lib/data/`, `src/lib/auth/`, and any module data layer starts with `import 'server-only'`. A convention guard test fails CI if this is missed. The rule prevents accidentally bundling server credentials or service-role logic into the client.
- **Naming convention.** {{TODO: snake_case in database / SQL / RPC params; camelCase in TypeScript. Document any deviations here. The data layer is responsible for converting between conventions; surfaces above the data layer see camelCase only.}}
- **Route groups.** {{TODO: list route groups and what each guards. Example: `app/(staff)` requires staff role; `app/(member)` requires authenticated member; `app/(public)` is unauthenticated. Each route group's `layout.tsx` enforces its guard via redirect.}}

